{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The traveling-salesman heuristic produces a route that is no more than 1.5x the length of the optimal route for inputs up to 20 stops.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is the heuristic algorithm itself (no required I/O). A pure in-process test can catch regressions by comparing heuristic length vs exact/known-optimal baselines on deterministic coordinate sets. Real network/OS/model behavior is not required.","test_description":"Call the route-heuristic function directly on a corpus of fixed stop sets (including edge geometries like clusters, line, circle, outliers). For each case, compute optimal tour length with an exact solver feasible for the case size (or precomputed optimal fixtures), then assert heuristic_length/optimal_length <= 1.5. Include cases up to 20 stops where optimal references are provided by fixtures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from the distance between consecutive stops and the configured average speed for the road type.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real risk is module wiring: distance output, road-type speed lookup, and time-window calculator can mismatch units or keys. A single-function unit test can miss those cross-module failures; no external API/OS behavior is needed.","test_description":"Run estimator through the real internal pipeline (distance module + road-type speed config + time-window computation) using local fixtures for route segments and road types. Assert per-segment and cumulative ETA values match expected minutes/hours, including mixed road types and unit-conversion edge cases.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a deterministic arithmetic/business-rule boundary. No I/O, subprocess, or external dependency is needed to expose real failures (comparison logic, rounding, excess calculation).","test_description":"Directly test the validator function with table-driven cases: equal-to-limit, just-under, just-over, and large-overage totals. Assert reject/accept decision and exact returned excess duration (including rounding/precision policy).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.78,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address in the list fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop and optimizes the remaining addresses, reporting which addresses were skipped.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"A pure mock can hide real HTTP/serialization contract issues (empty-results payload shape, status handling). Minimum realistic boundary is service + real HTTP client behavior against a controllable test server.","test_description":"Run the service end-to-end against a local HTTP geocoding stub server. Configure responses so one address returns an empty result set while others return coordinates. Assert output route excludes failed address, optimizer runs on remaining stops, and response includes the skipped-address report with correct identifiers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.3,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses in the input list are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure often occurs across deduplication, item-aggregation, and route-building modules. Unit tests of only dedupe logic can miss re-expansion or double-visit bugs later in pipeline. No real external infra is required.","test_description":"Feed the service pipeline with input containing duplicate addresses and distinct delivery items per duplicate. Assert the intermediate/returned stop list has one consolidated stop for that address, items are merged correctly, and final route contains that stop exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.27,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
